From b2955beada4180ffaa1bcc62e3b43e5a3fe18e8b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 08:23:49 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P6 (dar-aw2): gated rdtsc phase-prof for the hot ring
 RPC (server side)

Diagnostic only: behind DSERVER_RING_PHASE_PROF (default OFF, byte-identical off,
on top of DSERVER_RING_TRANSPORT). rdtsc brackets in ringServiceThread + publishReply
accumulate per-phase TSC cycles -- drain (consumer_begin + Message rebuild), dispatch
(callFromMessage), body (doWork minus publish), publish (publishReply) -- into ring-
gated atomic counters emitted in the stat-socket JSON (phase_*_cycles + phase_samples).
Metrics::rdtscCycles() helper; Thread::takeRingPublishCycles() hands the publish delta
back to ringServiceThread so body excludes it.

MEASURED (hot mach_reply_port, 30k calls, TSC 1.9962GHz, balanced):
  guest submit 510ns | server drain 296 | dispatch 647 | body 2260 | publish 32
  | wakeup 960 | guest observe 17  => ~4.7us total (reconciles with bench 4.84us).
=> transport is ~free (~855ns/18%); the floor is server Mach work: doWork() body 48%
+ callFromMessage dispatch 14%. Confirms the gist's opcode-fast-path hypothesis: a
specialized mach_reply_port path skipping Message-rebuild + microthread setup could cut
the floor toward ~1.5-2us. Wakeup 960ns is shared-host scheduler cost (shrinks pinned).
