From 4ef0a11e070825caed679ccf7e6d1b6edc0f0ce1 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 08:49:54 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P6.1 (dar-ohp): opcode fast path step 1 -- run
 non-blocking ring ops without the fiber

P6/dar-aw2 measured the hot ring mach_reply_port floor: ~48% of the 4.7us is doWork()'s
microthread fiber (stackPool.allocate + getcontext/makecontext/setcontext) wrapped around a
trivial port mint. Recon confirmed current_task()/current_thread() resolve via a duct-tape hook
reading the currentThreadVar thread-local -- NOT the fiber -- and mach_reply_port never blocks.

Thread::doWorkInline() (thread.cpp): establishes the SAME duct-tape context (currentThreadVar +
dtape_thread_entering) and runs the SAME processCall() (= dtape_mach_reply_port = the real XNU
mach_reply_port trap -- no reimplemented Mach code, per the gist's "good variant") on the
CURRENT main-loop stack, with the same exception containment + metrics as microthreadWorker and
the same essential completion cleanup as doneWorking (dtape_thread_exiting, _activeCall clear,
interrupt scheduling, release). CONTRACT: caller guarantees the op never suspends (no fiber to
return to); a suspend is detected + logged loudly. Returns false if it declines (not the simple
fresh-call case) so the caller falls back to the generic doWork() fiber path.

ringServiceThread (call.cpp): for allowlisted no-block ops (mach_reply_port, task_self_trap)
calls doWorkInline() instead of doWork(); everything else takes the generic path unchanged.
Escape hatches (gist-mandated): DARLING_SERVER_FAST_OPS=0 disables ALL fast paths;
DARLING_SERVER_FAST_MACH_REPLY_PORT=0 disables just mach_reply_port's -- so the ring can run
without specialized inline semantics if a bug surfaces. Default ON when the ring is on.

RED->GREEN gate (tests/ring_fastpath_gate_test.c, wired into run-ring-shm-validate.sh): pins the
allowlist + that both escape hatches actually gate eligibility; -DFASTPATH_NO_HATCH (ignores the
hatches) arm must fail. RED proven, GREEN after.

LIVE A/B (same build, escape hatch flipped; deployed locally, NOT pushed): mach_reply_port fast
inline ~3.2-3.9us vs generic fiber (FAST_OPS=0) ~4.2-5.0us = ~900ns/~21% saved, null=0 both
(60k mint+free clean = identical port semantics). Phase-prof: server body 2260ns -> 1589ns
(the fiber removal); residual body is real ipc_port_alloc + dtape enter/exit, not wrapper.
Fork-storm build 3/3 DONE (doWorkInline cleanup doesn't regress dar-l8k/dar-6x4). Prod restored
OFF. Step 2 (full opcode path skipping Message-rebuild + callFromMessage) would target ~2-2.5us.
