From 04d9e6f1bcb0912dfc9a7f8c584f5d139a2174c0 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 13:11:57 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P5-bulk (dar-1il.1): ring-migrate mach_port_allocate
 + insert_right; no-silent-drop invariant gate; S2C-deferred-reply ring fix

Migrates two more Tier-1 port/right bookkeeping ops onto the shared-memory ring
(generic fiber doWork path, NOT no-fiber inline -- same as mach_port_mod_refs):
  - mach_port_allocate (callnum 40): {target,right,name-ptr} body, header-only
    reply; the allocated name travels via the guest-memory write the generic Call
    path already performs (out-pointer), identical to UDS.
  - mach_port_insert_right (callnum 43): {target,name,poly,polyPoly}, header-only.

NO-SILENT-DROP INVARIANT (the prerequisite gate the bead demands): the set of
ring-eligible C2S opcodes is now a SINGLE shared source of truth -- the X-macro
DSERVER_RING_C2S_OPCODES in rpc-supplement.h -- consumed by BOTH the server
allowlist (ringServiceThread `eligible`) and the guest dispatch. A guest op the
server doesn't allowlist would be silently consumed + dropped -> guest stranded on
its ring reply-wait = wedge. ring_drift_gate_test.c (RED arm -DDRIFT_GUEST_EXTRA)
pins guest-set == server-set so they can't drift.

KEY NEGATIVE FINDING -- mach_port_deallocate is DELIBERATELY NOT ring-migrated:
under launchd's real workload it destroys ports backing mapped regions, which
drives a vm munmap server-to-client (S2C) upcall to the CALLING thread. A thread
parked on a ring reply is not in a recvmsg and cannot service an S2C call, so the
server microthread blocks on the S2C reply semaphore while the guest blocks in the
ring futex-wait -> deadlock (observed: launchd wedges before shellspawn ever comes
up). New membership rule (rpc-supplement.h): a ring-eligible op must NEVER trigger
an S2C upcall to the caller. deallocate stays on UDS, where the caller's recvmsg
services the S2C.

Also a latent-correctness fix surfaced while chasing the wedge: a ring-originated
call that performs an S2C upcall has its reply DEFERRED (_deferReplyForS2C); the
deferred-reply flush in _s2cPerform() unconditionally sent it over UDS, so a
ring-waiting guest would never wake. Factored the ring-vs-UDS publish decision into
Thread::_publishReplyToRingLocked() and call it from BOTH pushCallReply() and the
deferred flush, so a deferred reply for a ring call goes back onto the ring.

Validation (ring-ON vs TRUE-UDS, prod-off non-ring stack):
  - 14-edge A/B byte-IDENTICAL kern_return_t for allocate/insert_right/deallocate
    (allocate RECEIVE/PORT_SET/DEAD_NAME=0x0 name_ok; illegal right=0x12; insert
    MAKE_SEND=0x0, invalid name=0xf, illegal disp=0x11; all deallocate edges match).
  - allocate p50 ~2.8us vs UDS ~14.4us (~5.1x); insert_right p50 ~2.1us vs ~13.8us
    (~6.4x).
  - counters clean: ring_fast_fail=0 ring_s2c_full=0 ring_fast_suspend=0
    clients_blocked_in_rpc=0.
  - boot + shellspawn OK; fork-storm 3/3 RESULT=DONE .o=200/200 clients_blocked=0.

RED->GREEN gates updated + committed: ring_fastpath_gate_test.c (allowlist now
driven by the shared macro; allocate/insert_right C2S-allowlisted + NOT inline;
deallocate NOT allowlisted) and the new ring_drift_gate_test.c.
