From d314907d84e77c7a9720d0fd0fe5f9d6548c75bc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 14:00:40 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 dar-1il.2: remove mod_refs from ring (S2C-deadlock) +
 tie C2S opcode-set to ring ABI

Default-ON BLOCKER audit (gist 09a2c447). Three changes:

ITEM 1 (blocker) -- remove mach_port_mod_refs from the C2S ring allowlist.
mod_refs is destroy-capable: mod_refs(right, delta<0) dropping the last user-ref
of a receive right destroys the port, and destroying a mapped-region-backed port
drives a vm-munmap server-to-client (S2C) upcall to the caller -- the SAME hazard
that sank mach_port_deallocate (a thread parked on a ring reply is not in recvmsg
and cannot service an S2C call -> deadlock). The hazard is a SIDE EFFECT of certain
args, not the return code, and is undecidable before the ipc_space lock is held and
the refcount known (i.e. after mutation begins), so it cannot ride the ring until a
proven-safe subset is gated. The "14-edge byte-identical kern_return_t" A/B in
dar-1il.1 destroyed only bare ports and so did NOT prove safety. mod_refs is now
UDS-only (guest wrapper reverted, helper removed, NEITHER C2S- nor inline-eligible).
Ring set is now {task_self_trap, mach_reply_port, mach_port_allocate,
mach_port_insert_right}.

ITEM 2 -- tie the C2S opcode set to the ring ABI / attach handshake.
The shared DSERVER_RING_C2S_OPCODES macro only prevents guest/server drift when both
are built from the same header; an old-server/new-guest skew still drifts -> silent
per-op drop -> wedge. Fold the opcode set into a 64-bit FNV hash both sides compute
from their own compiled macro, carry it in the control block (c2s_opcode_hash), and
have the server REJECT the ring at attach (dserver_ring_reject_opcode_set -> the
thread uses UDS for everything, never a silent per-op drop) on mismatch. The struct
grew, so bump DSERVER_RING_ABI_VERSION 2 -> 3. The hash fn references callnums (from
the generated rpc.h) so it is guarded by _DARLINGSERVER_API_H_; the server build
always has rpc.h in scope, so the validator check is always active in production.

ITEM 3 -- (harness, separate untracked guest file) side-effect/lifecycle A/B for
allocate/insert_right asserting STATE after the op (mach_port_type bitmask, user-ref
counts, name reclamation, no garbage on error edges), not just the kern_return_t.

RED->GREEN gates committed with the change:
- ring_drift_gate_test.c + ring_fastpath_gate_test.c: mod_refs pinned OUT of the C2S
  set (sanity asserts mod_refs absent like deallocate); RED arm -DC2S_READD_MODREFS
  re-adds it and the "mod_refs NOT C2S-allowlisted" assertion fails.
- ring_shm_validate_test.cpp + ring_attach_check_test.cpp: opcode-set hash mismatch
  rejected (flip one bit -> reject_opcode_set); matching hash accepted (non-vacuous).
- ring_wake_predicates_test.c: ABI version assertion updated to 3.
- run-ring-shm-validate.sh: lifts GEN_RPC discovery up front (the validator now needs
  callnums for the hash), threads -I$GEN_RPC into the validate/attach/datapath/wake
  arms, and swaps the mod_refs C2S RED arm to -DC2S_READD_MODREFS. Full suite: all
  perf#18 ring gates OK.

Live validation (ring ON, booted): boot healthy + shellspawn up (no wedge); ring
attached (opcode hash accepted), ring_fast_suspend/fail/fallback/s2c_full/
clients_blocked all 0. allocate/insert_right A/B vs true UDS (prod-OFF build):
EVERY EDGE (kern_return_t) AND SE (type/refcount/reclamation) line byte-identical.
Latency: ring p50 alloc ~3.5us / insert ~2.8us vs UDS ~15.4us / ~21.4us. Fork-storm
3/3 RESULT=DONE .o=200/200 clients_blocked=0 (no dar-l8k/dar-6x4 regression).

call.cpp staged with the foreign DARLING_FORK_TIMELINE hunks filtered out.
Local only; nothing pushed.
