 fi
 
+# --- P8 D3 (dar-1il.3.1.1): the END-TO-END real-dylib duplex selftest is a SYSTEM test (it must boot
+#     darling + use the deployed guest dylib + real server), so it cannot run inside this hermetic host
+#     suite. It lives in run-duplex-real-selftest.sh and is part of the D3 acceptance run, NOT this
+#     suite. Pointer only:
+echo "note: the real-dylib duplex selftest (D3 end-to-end) is a SYSTEM gate -- run separately:"
+echo "      bash tests/run-duplex-real-selftest.sh both   # RED (no-pump, no-wedge) then GREEN (PASS + counter)"
+echo
+
 echo "all perf#18 ring gates: OK"

From d906bc6e5fba92f6168ab3db99c335b6754f9281 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 05:19:13 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#18 P8 D4 (dar-1il.3.2.1): mach_port_deallocate via the
 duplex lane (server) + parent counters

Migrate mach_port_deallocate onto the duplex lane (the destroy-capable / caller-S2C op the lane
was built for) behind a default-OFF cap + hatch, with the brutal-acceptance gate proven first.

HARD GATE (logic, RED->GREEN before any wiring): tests/ring_duplex_dealloc_gate_test.c proves the
two deallocate-specific properties -- (4) the destroy side effect is applied EXACTLY ONCE, no
partial-mutation-then-UDS double-effect (RED -DDUPLEX_PARTIAL_THEN_UDS fails); (5) a dropped/lost
upcall reply FAILS CLOSED + BOUNDED, never a fabricated success (RED -DDUPLEX_FABRICATE_ON_DROP
fails). Wired into run-ring-shm-validate.sh.

ABI v4->v5: DUPLEX_CAP_DEALLOCATE + DUPLEX_UPCALL_MUNMAP + DUPLEX_DECLINE sentinel reply code +
typed mailbox payload (duplex_upcall_addr/len, duplex_reply_errno) + publish_munmap_upcall /
publish_munmap_reply helpers. v4<->v5 rejects at attach (clean all-UDS). ring_wake_predicates_test
asserts v5; ring_duplex_roundtrip_test extended with a lossless munmap-payload roundtrip.

SERVER: _s2cTryDuplexMunmapLocked publishes the munmap S2C into the mailbox (requires the
DEALLOCATE cap). _s2cPerform routes a duplex parent's munmap S2C through the mailbox + parks the
fiber on _s2cReplySempahore exactly as the UDS S2C path; _drainDuplexReply's REAL-op branch
synthesizes a dserver_s2c_reply_munmap_t + ups the semaphore (the real fiber resume), and on
mis-correlation synthesizes a FAILED munmap reply (no fabricated success). ringServiceThread routes
deallocate from a cap-capable caller onto the fiber with _ringDuplexParentActive set; declines
pre-dispatch (DUPLEX_DECLINE reply -> guest UDS-falls-back, no mutation) if not cap-capable or bad
shape. _pickS2CThread returns currentThread() for the current process, so the munmap S2C is
delivered to the same (parent) thread -- the mailbox/park design is correct. New counters
ring_duplex_parent (op rode the lane) + ring_duplex_decline (pre-dispatch decline).

RESULT (honest): the deallocate RIDES the duplex lane (ring_duplex_parent=11 in a live A/B) with
side effects BYTE-IDENTICAL to UDS, fork-storm 3/3, Lane-1 fast path unaffected, isolation holds.
But mach_port_deallocate does NOT drive a munmap S2C in Darling (mach_make_memory_entry_64 is
stubbed), so ring_duplex_s2c stays 0 -- the dar-1il.1 deadlock cannot be reproduced via this op
here. The live deadlock-CURE proof is therefore N/A for deallocate; the machinery is correct +
safe (fail-closed, pre-mutation decline) and kept default-OFF. The real S2C-cure proof target is
vm_deallocate (a separate op that does drive a caller munmap S2C) -- a follow-up bead.
