munmap occurs under a UDS parent (mach_msg_overwrite OOL teardown) -> reachable
but UDS-only today (serviced via recvmsg, no ring-deadlock); it becomes a hazard
only if that op is ever ring-migrated. The sideband is the prerequisite for that.

Live cure PROVEN end-to-end (synthetic warm proof, default-OFF, env-gated
DARLING_GUEST_D6_MUNMAP_PROOF=1 + server DARLING_SERVER_D5_VMDEALLOC_PROOF):
a test guest maps a real page then sends vm_deallocate of it over the duplex ring
with target==self; the server _kernelrpc_mach_vm_deallocate_trap resolves target
-> current_task -> vm_map_remove -> task_free_pages -> a REAL _s2cPerform munmap
that (caller ring-parked) rides the duplex mailbox; the guest pump runs the real
munmap(2) on the caller thread; the server fiber resumes; the final parent reply
returns over the ring. Counters: ring_duplex_s2c=3, ring_duplex_vmdealloc_final=3,
s2c_munmap_ring_parent=3, timeout=0. RED (no guest pump): bounded, no s2c
increment, no wedge.

Server-side fail-closed deadline (gist failure policy): _s2cTryDuplexMunmapLocked
arms a 5s CLOCK_MONOTONIC deadline; _drainDuplexReply resumes the fiber with a
FAILED reply (ETIMEDOUT) + counts ring_duplex_vmdealloc_timeout + clears + disarms
if no correlated reply arrives -- never a leaked fiber, never fabricated success.

