A/B of the guest per-process lane cap GR_MAX_LANES ∈ {64,96,128,256} via a
compile-time #define override (guest-only cap; server _ringThreads is unbounded,
so only the dylib+dyld vary and the D17 census server is reused). No lane reclaim,
no opcode-set change, no duplex/psynch/mach_msg_overwrite. Source reverted to the
committed 64u baseline; test/doc artifacts only.

Workload = the D17-rerun exhaustion probe (ONE process × N threads hammering the
D10 self-trap ring ops). Results (exhausted across 3 runs; all health counters 0):
  64 @96  -> exhausted ~39,300, 65% ring   (the D17-rerun result reproduced)
  96 @96  -> exhausted 1202,   98% ring    (a 96-worker proc actually wants ~97 lanes:
                                            96 workers + 1 runtime helper thread)
  128@96  -> exhausted 0,      100% ring    <- proposal condition met
  256@96  -> exhausted 0,      100% ring    (identical to 128; no benefit, no cost)
  256@200 -> exhausted 0,      100% ring    (headroom; 726K rpcs, all health 0)
  128@200 -> exhausted ~87,250, 63% ring    (128 is right-sized, NOT infinite)

Memory/layout cost: table BSS = 40 B × GR_MAX_LANES (64->2.5KB .. 256->10KB, ×2
images, negligible). Real cost is per-ATTACHED-lane = 1 page (4KB) + 1 memfd +
1 wake eventfd, allocated lazily; 64->128 costs +≤256KB shmem + 128 fds only for a
process that genuinely goes wide. No regressions at any cap value.

PROPOSAL: adopt GR_MAX_LANES=128 as the new default — cures the 96-thread workload
(exhausted=0, 100% ring, no regressions) with negligible cost and real headroom over
the observed 97-lane demand. Caveat: 128 is right-sized not infinite (>128 concurrent
eligible-op threads still exhaust); the structural fix for churny/very-wide procs is
lane reclaim on thread-exit (reclaimed=0 everywhere here) = the natural D18b, out of
scope per spec. One-line #define, ABI-neutral.

Adds tests/PERF18-D18A-LANES-SCALING.md + 6 snapshots + run-d18a-lanes-ab.sh.
Prod restored + md5-verified. HEADs darlingserver @615636c / xnu @a1425a0.
