Splits a real build's wall time into A) lifecycle/spawn-exec churn,
B) compiler/emulation CPU, C) fs/path lookup; ranks by TOTAL WALL TIME.

Findings (200-file clang -j8 build, warm server, bpftrace lifecycle census):
- clang = 78.8% of build wall (10.99s/13.95s), 400 procs; bash 10.8%, make
  9.9%; every utility <=0.1% each. Spawn/exec churn (bucket A) is tiny in a
  real build.
- clang-only: wall 11.33s vs on-CPU 4.54s => 40% on-CPU / 60% off-CPU. That
  off-CPU is NOT RPC (~39 RPCs/child, ~0.5ms/child, ring health counters all
  0) and NOT sync (perf#19: futex 0.067% of wall). It is clang doing clang
  work — CPU-bound compile under emulation + -j8 oversubscription.
- Lifecycle tax IS visible in synthetic trivial-proc workloads (fork-storm:
  288 /usr/bin/true = 10.77s = 37ms/no-op-proc, 82% off-CPU; path_helper
  execs every shell, costs more wall than the command) — but dwarfed 400:1
  by clang in a parallel compile.

VERDICT B: next lever is CPU profiling of clang/cc1 under emulation
(perf record), NOT lifecycle. Secondary (only for shell/fork-heavy targets
like configure/brew): a bounded per-process-startup bead (path_helper +
dyld library-search stat). Explicitly NOT next: more ring opcode migration,
sync/futex, duplex/mach_msg_overwrite. brew confirmed not a bounded
benchmark (reference only).

RECON: no behavior change; prod binaries untouched; ring default GR_MAX_LANES
unchanged. Instruments p20a-lifecycle.bt + p20a-clangcpu.bt + stat snapshots.
