From 10399118b856807b5c481183633cf872084a9de2 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Wed, 1 Jul 2026 03:34:20 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?perf#21a:=20cc1=20CPU=20attribution=20=E2=80=94?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=20verdict=20B,=20fork=20fd-table=20copy=20is=20#1=20lever?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Option-1 method (no native/Docker baseline): attribute WHERE inside the
Darling-run clang time goes. Constraints found: no PMU (cycles/instructions
<not supported>, virtualized host, no IPC); guest Mach-O userspace symbols
don't resolve in perf (DSO-level only); kernel symbols resolve via sudo perf.

Findings (200-file clang -j8 build):
- CPU is kernel-heavy: user 3.08s vs sys 5.72s (~65% in kernel); 773K
  page-faults.
- DSO self-time (comm=mldr, relative): clang 37.2%, dyld 21.4%,
  libsystem_kernel 14.6%, platform 9.2%, malloc 8.6%. Real LLVM is only
  ~37% — NOT dominated by compiler work.
- #1 on-CPU symbol = [k] dup_fd at 13.3% (copy fd-table on fork).
  ROOT CAUSE: mldr.c:601,625 places Darling control fds (dserver socket,
  lifetime pipe, eventfds) from the TOP of fd space downward
  (fd = RLIMIT_NOFILE-1 = 1048575; confirmed a socket at fd 1048575 in
  117/184 guest procs). One fd at index 1048575 forces a 1,048,576-slot
  (~8.4MB) kernel fd table; every fork() does an ~8.4MB vmalloc+copy in
  dup_fd for 3-40 real fds => ~3.4GB of fd-table churn per build.
- Syscall TIME is mostly blocking wait (recvmsg 28%/wait4 27%/select 12%/
  epoll 8%), latency-hidden under -j8, NOT an on-CPU bucket (per perf#19).

VERDICT B: Darling-runtime overhead is real; ONE concrete high-value lever
= stop forcing a 1M-slot fd table (place control fds low/packed, or cap
guest RLIMIT_NOFILE, or compact reserved band). ~13% of guest on-CPU on
real builds. Next bead perf#21b (design + fix + revalidate; must preserve
the macOS-low-fd invariant the high fds exist for). NOT next: more
ring/sync/psynch, "optimize clang" (only 37%, no baseline/PMU), dyld bead
(possible 2nd lever after fd fix).

RECON: no code change; prod untouched; no kernel sysctl persisted.
