Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Split the post-D21b dyld/pagefault/startup bucket on the 200-file clang
-j8 workload (compact-fd mldr, dup_fd dead). Static: sys_fork = real COW
clone; sys_posix_spawn ALSO forks then execs (NOT vfork/CLONE_VFORK) --
so the "fork big AS then exec" pattern is real; measured how much it costs.

Kernel mm split (kprobe timing, 3 builds):
  exit_mmap (AS teardown)   1.488s  88%  2508 @593us   DOMINANT
  copy_page_range (fork COW) 0.203s 12%  237935 @853ns  cheap, NOT lever
  => exit_mmap = 7.3x fork PTE-copy
Faults 2.69M (minor 2.63M, MAJOR 155~0 => warm cache, not disk).
~206 mmaps/process; ~212 file-maps/exec; same dyld+libsystem set repeated
across ~415 procs/build.

CRITICAL FORK RESOLVED: fork PTE-copy before immediate exec is only 12%
(COW copies pte-entries, 853ns) -- a spawn/vfork fast path would recover
~1.5% on-CPU, not worth it. The cost is TEARDOWN + repeated per-process
mapping: every short-lived proc maps ~206 identical library regions,
faults them in, unmaps on exit, x415/build. Same root feeds both the
kernel mm 12.8% and the userspace dyld 21%.

VERDICT E: process reuse / teardown avoidance (persistent worker) is the
next lever -- attacks the 88% teardown AND the 21% dyld at once by not
re-running the loader 415x. NOT A (spawn/vfork, only 12%), NOT B (dyld
cache is a symptom), NOT C/D (faults warm/cheap). Next bead perf#23:
compiler/loader process-reuse feasibility (recon->design). NOT touched:
NOFILE cap, ring, psynch, fd-band, clang, dyld opt. No code changes.
